# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: a-sand-county-almanac
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/a-sand-county-almanac] The book has had over two million copies printed and has been translated into at least fourteen languages.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/a-sand-county-almanac] It has informed and changed the environmental movement and stimulated a widespread interest in ecology as a science.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/a-sand-county-almanac] In the original publishing, the book begins with a set of essays under the heading "Sand County Almanac," which is divided into twelve segments, one for each month.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/a-sand-county-almanac] These essays mostly follow the changes in the ecology on Leopold's farm near Baraboo, Wisconsin.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/a-sand-county-almanac] (There is, in fact, no "Sand County" in Wisconsin.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/a-sand-county-almanac] The term "sand counties" refers to a section of the state marked by sandy soils).
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/a-sand-county-almanac] There are anecdotes and observations about flora and fauna reactions to the seasons as well as mentions of conservation topics.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/a-sand-county-almanac] The second section of the book, "Sketches Here and There," shifts the rhetorical focus from time to place.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/a-sand-county-almanac] The essays are thematically organized around farms and wildernesses in Canada, Mexico and the United States.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/a-sand-county-almanac] Some of these essays are autobiographical.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/a-sand-county-almanac] "Red Legs Kicking," for example, recounts Leopold's boyhood experience of hunting in Iowa.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/a-sand-county-almanac] The seminal essay "Thinking Like a Mountain" recalls another hunting experience later in life that was formative for Leopold's later views.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/a-sand-county-almanac] Here Leopold describes the death of a she-wolf killed by his party during a time when conservationists were operating under the assumption that elimination of top predators would make game plentiful.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/a-sand-county-almanac] The essay provides a non-technical characterization of the trophic cascade where the removal of single species carries serious implications for the rest of the ecosystem.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/a-sand-county-almanac] The book ends with a section of philosophical essays grouped together under the heading "The Upshot".
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/a-sand-county-almanac] Here Leopold explores ironies of conservation: in order to promote wider appreciation of wild nature and engender necessary political support, one encourages recreational usage of wilderness that ultimately destroys it.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/a-sand-county-almanac] Musings on "trophies" contrasts the way that some need a physical specimen to prove their conquest into the wilderness, though photographs may be less damaging than a trophy head to be mounted on the wall.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/a-sand-county-almanac] He suggests that the best trophy is the experience of wilderness itself, along with its character-building aspects.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/a-sand-county-almanac] Leopold also rails against the way that policy makers need to find an economic motive for conservation.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/a-sand-county-almanac] In the concluding essay, "The Land Ethic", Leopold delves into a more appropriate rationale for conservation.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/a-sand-county-almanac] In "The Ecological Conscience" section, he wrote: "Conservation is a state of harmony between men and land." Leopold felt it was generally agreed that more conservation education was needed; however quantity and content were up for debate.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/a-sand-county-almanac] He believed that land is not a commodity to be possessed; rather, humans must have mutual respect for Earth in order not to destroy it.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/a-sand-county-almanac] He philosophizes that humans will cease to be free if they have no wild spaces in which to roam.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/a-sand-county-almanac] In a 1990 poll of the membership by the American Nature Study Society, *A Sand County Almanac* and Rachel Carson's *Silent Spring* stand alone as the two most venerated and significant environmental books of the 20th century.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/a-sand-county-almanac] The book was little noticed when published but, during the environmental awakening of the 1970s, a paperback edition turned into a surprise bestseller.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/a-sand-county-almanac] The book has had immense popular influence and has been described as: "one of the benchmark titles of the ecological movement", "a major influence on American attitudes toward our natural environment", "recognized as a classic piece of outdoor literature, rivaling Thoreau's *Walden*".
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/a-sand-county-almanac] The book has also had great influence on environmental thinkers: "along with *Walden* and Rachel Carson’s *Silent Spring*, one of the main intellectual underpinnings of environmentalism in America".
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/a-sand-county-almanac] The book has "attracted such overwhelming attention from environmental philosophers as a source of inspiration and ideas".
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/a-sand-county-almanac] Leopold's home, Aldo Leopold Shack and Farm, was listed on the U.S.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/a-sand-county-almanac] National Register of Historic Places in 1978, and was uplisted to National Historic Landmark status in 2009.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold-shack-and-farm] The **Aldo Leopold Shack and Farm** is a historic farm on Levee Road in rural Sauk County, Wisconsin, United States.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold-shack-and-farm] The property was acquired in the 1930s as a family summer retreat by the noted conservationist and writer Aldo Leopold and is the landscape that inspired his conservation ethic and the writing of his best-known work, *A Sand County Almanac*.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold-shack-and-farm] The property is now owned and managed by the Aldo Leopold Foundation, which provides tours and other educational programs on the property and the adjacent visitors center.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold-shack-and-farm] It was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1978 and was designated a National Historic Landmark in 2009.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold-shack-and-farm] Leopold began buying land here in 1935, acquiring more than 150 acres (61 ha) by the time of his death in 1948.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold-shack-and-farm] The family continued to acquire land until 1970, including a small island in the river.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold-shack-and-farm] The family then donated the property to the Aldo Leopold Foundation.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold-shack-and-farm] The property is about 264 acres (107 ha) on the south bank of the Wisconsin River northeast of Baraboo, Wisconsin.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold-shack-and-farm] The property is roughly rectangular in shape, extending south from the river, and roughly bisected by Levee Road.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold-shack-and-farm] The foundation has a visitors' center about 0.5 miles (0.80 km) east of the property at the junction of Levee and Schemp Roads.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold-shack-and-farm] The farm is biologically diverse, with floodplain forest and marshland and former fields that have been restored to native prairie.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold-shack-and-farm] The principal built feature of the farm is the former chicken coop, set midway between Levee Road and the river, where Leopold spent his time; there is also a small outhouse nearby.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold-shack-and-farm] The soil in the region is sandy, the result of deposition during the Cambrian Period that was reworked by the Wisconsin glaciation.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold-shack-and-farm] Leopold's writings on conservation and the environment were significantly influenced by this landscape.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold-shack-and-farm] *A Sand County Almanac*, a compilation of his writings, is widely regarded as one of the most influential works on conservationism of the 20th century.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold-shack-and-farm] Leopold wrote the essay, "Marshland Elegy," in 1937 which warned that sandhill cranes could become extinct in Wisconsin and the upper Midwest as the species had dwindled to just 25 breeding pairs in Wisconsin.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Leopold was influential in the development of modern environmental ethics and in the movement for wilderness conservation.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] His ethics of nature and wildlife preservation had a profound impact on the environmental movement, with his ecocentric or holistic ethics regarding land.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] He emphasized biodiversity and ecology and was a founder of the science of wildlife management.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Rand Aldo Leopold was born in Burlington, Iowa, on January 11, 1887.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] His father, Carl Leopold, was a businessman who made walnut desks and was first cousin to his wife, Clara Starker.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Charles Starker, who was Carl's father and Clara's uncle, came to the United States from Germany and studied engineering and architecture.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Rand Aldo was named after two of his father's business partners—C.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Rand and Aldo Sommers—although he eventually dropped the use of "Rand".
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] The Leopold family included younger siblings Mary Luize, Carl Starker, and Frederic.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Leopold's first language was German, although he mastered English at an early age.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Aldo Leopold's early life was highlighted by the outdoors.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Carl would take his children on excursions into the woods and taught his oldest son woodcraft and hunting.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Aldo showed an aptitude for observation, spending hours counting and cataloging birds near his home.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] His sister Mary later said that even as a young child, "He was very much an outdoorsman, even in his extreme youth.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] He was always out climbing around the bluffs, or going down to the river, or going across the river into the woods." He attended Prospect Hill Elementary, where he ranked at the top of his class, and then, the overcrowded Burlington High School.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Every August, the family vacationed in Michigan on the forested Marquette Island in Lake Huron, which the children took to exploring.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] In 1900, Gifford Pinchot, head of the new Division of Forestry in the Department of Agriculture, donated money to Yale University to begin one of the nation's first forestry schools.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Hearing of this development, teenage Leopold decided he wanted to become a forester.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] His parents agreed to let him attend The Lawrenceville School, a preparatory college in New Jersey, to improve his chances of admission to Yale.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] The Burlington High School principal wrote in a reference letter to the headmaster at Lawrenceville saying that Leopold was "as earnest a boy as we have in school... painstaking in his work....
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Moral character above reproach." He arrived at his new school in January 1904, shortly before he turned 17.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] He was considered an attentive student, although he was again drawn to the outdoors.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Lawrenceville was suitably rural, and Leopold spent much time mapping the area and studying its wildlife.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Leopold studied at the Lawrenceville School for a year, during which time he was accepted to Yale.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Since the Yale School of Forestry granted only graduate degrees, Leopold first enrolled in Sheffield Scientific School's preparatory forestry courses for his undergraduate studies, in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] While Leopold was able to explore the woods and fields of Lawrenceville daily, sometimes to the detriment of his studying, at Yale he had little opportunity to do so; his studies and social life made his outdoor trips few and far between.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Leopold graduated from the Yale Forestry School in 1909.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] In 1909, Leopold was assigned to the Forest Service's District 3 in the Arizona and New Mexico territories.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] At first, he was a forest assistant at the Apache National Forest in the Arizona Territory.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] In 1911, he was transferred to the Carson National Forest in northern New Mexico.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Leopold was stationed in New Mexico until 1924 because he was developing the first comprehensive management plan for the Grand Canyon, writing the Forest Service's first game and fish handbook, and proposing Gila Wilderness Area, the first wilderness area in the Forest Service system.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Furthermore, Leopold encouraged many changes within New Mexico and Arizona through his time spent in the region developing these plans.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] In 1916, Leopold conducted a speaking tour across New Mexico to encourage the formation of wildlife protection associations among local sportsmen.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] The tour began in Silver City, where Leopold met Miles W.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Buford, who went on to establish the Sportsmen's Association of Southwestern New Mexico.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Leopold proposed the creation of a statewide organization, the New Mexico Game Protection Association (NMGPA), which gained support in several cities including Rincon, El Paso, Alamogordo, Cloudcroft, Carlsbad, Roswell, and Albuquerque.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] In March 1916, the NMGPA held its first convention, attracting over 1,000 members.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] The association adopted three goals: removing game warden appointments from political influence, establishing game refuges within national forests, and implementing a balance of predators.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Following the formation of the NMGPA, Leopold returned to his duties with the U.S.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] After the passage of the Term Permit Act, he began siting and surveying locations in Arizona for private recreational development.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] During this time, he also promoted and helped establish Game Protection Associations in Arizona towns such as Flagstaff, Springerville, Tucson, and Payson.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] In January 1918, Leopold became Secretary of the Albuquerque Chamber of Commerce.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] In this role, he supported various initiatives, including the inclusion of labor organizations in the chamber, the promotion of Hispanic and Pueblo architectural styles, and the drainage of parts of the Rio Grande Valley to expand agricultural land.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Leopold rejoined the Forest Service on August 1, 1919, as Assistant District Forester in Charge of Operations, overseeing Region 3, which included 11 national forests.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] During this period, he became concerned with soil erosion in areas such as the Prescott and Carson National Forests.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] In December 1923, he authored *The Watershed Handbook*, a guide for field staff addressing watershed management and recommending the regulation of livestock based on watershed conditions.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Just a few months into his new role, Leopold's superior, District Forester Paul Redington, left Region 3 and was succeeded by Frank C.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Pooler—who openly expressed doubts about Leopold's suitability for the position.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Pooler even arranged a new post for Leopold in a different region.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] However, Leopold stood his ground and declined the offer, choosing to stay in Albuquerque and New Mexico, where his family and numerous ongoing projects were deeply rooted.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Leopold's management plan was visionary for its time, emphasizing sustainable use and ecological preservation.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] He planned to make regulations with tourism, resource protection, recreational planning, and the long-term vision of the park.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] He felt that there needed to be a control of commercial enterprises, such as shops and concessions because he described them as "repugnant" to the canyon's natural character.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] He suggested there should be designated areas for visitor facilities to minimize environmental disruption.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Additionally, He advocated for the cleanup of garbage and sewage to restore the Colorado River's water quality.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Previously, there was history of people dumping garbage in the river.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] He emphasized preserving the canyon's geological and ecological features, including its stratified rock formations and native flora and fauna.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Leopold's plan for recreational planning was to outline strategies for “primitive recreation,” such as hiking, hunting, and fishing, to allow visitors to experience the canyon's wilderness without degrading it.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] He recommended trail development to improve access while protecting sensitive areas.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Finally, his long-term vision was to prioritized the “greatest good for the greatest number in the long run,” aligning with U.S.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] He laid the groundwork for future park management by advocating for a balance between human enjoyment and ecological health.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Wildlife management was largely unregulated, with game and fish populations often depleted due to overhunting, habitat destruction, and lack of coordinated oversight.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Leopold recognized the need for a systematic approach to manage wildlife resources.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] In the handbook, Leopold detailed a section on wildlife population management where he provided a guideline for monitoring and regulating game species, such as deer, elk, and fish, to prevent overharvesting.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] He emphasized sustainable hunting and fishing practices to maintain population health.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Additionally, he wrote a section on habitat conservation which he stressed the importance of preserving habitats, including forests, rivers, and wetlands, to support wildlife.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] He included recommendations for mitigating the impacts of grazing and logging on game and fish habitats.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] In a section about ecological balance, he introduced early concepts of predator-prey dynamics reflecting on his observations of ecological consequences when predators like wolves were eradicated.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] He advocated for a holistic approach to land management considering wildlife as part of the broader ecosystem.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Forest Service rangers to collect data on wildlife populations and enforce regulations.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] He proposed coordination with local communities and hunters to promote conservation awareness.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] In 1921, Leopold published an article in the *Journal of Forestry* titled “The Wilderness and Its Place in Forest Recreational Policy,” arguing for the preservation of roadless areas within national forests.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] He proposed the Gila as a prime candidate, envisioning it as a space free from roads, motorized vehicles, and industrial development.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] He recommended setting aside 750,000 acres of the Gila National Forest headwaters, an area characterized by canyons, mesas, and diverse wildlife, including elk, deer, and trout.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Leopold's proposal gained traction, and in 1924, the Forest Service approved the designation of 755,000 acres as the Gila Wilderness Area, the first such area in the world.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Leopold saw the Gila as a living laboratory for ecological health, where natural processes like predator-prey dynamics could unfold without human interference.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] This reflected his early understanding of trophic cascades, later detailed in his essay “Thinking Like a Mountain.” He also valued the Gila for its cultural significance, offering a space for Americans to reconnect with the frontier experience through self-reliant recreation.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] On April 5, 1923, he was elected an associate member (now called "professional member") of the Boone and Crockett Club, a wildlife conservation organization founded by Theodore Roosevelt and George Bird Grinnell.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] In 1924, he accepted transfer to the U.S.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Forest Products Laboratory in Madison, Wisconsin, and became an associate director.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] In 1933, he was appointed Professor of Game Management in the Agricultural Economics Department at the University of Wisconsin, the first such professorship of wildlife management.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] At the same time he was named Research Director of the University of Wisconsin–Madison Arboretum.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Leopold and other members of the first Arboretum Committee initiated a research agenda around re-establishing "original Wisconsin" landscape and plant communities, particularly those that predated European settlement, such as tallgrass prairie and oak savanna.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Under the Oberlaender Trust of the Carl Schurz Memorial Foundation, Leopold was part of the 1935 group of six U.S.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Forest Service associates who toured the forests of Germany and Austria.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Leopold was invited specifically to study game management, and this was his first and only time abroad.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] His European observations would have a significant impact on his ecological thinking, leading him to view the German policies in favor of blocks of monoculture trees in straight lines as a cautionary tale leading to soil degradation and an overall loss of biodiversity.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] After 1935, Leopold was no longer working for the U.S.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Forest Service; he had left the agency in 1928 to work independently and later became a professor at the University of Wisconsin.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Leopold married Estella Bergere, the daughter of a well known ranching family in New Mexico, in northern New Mexico in 1912 and they had five children together.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] They lived in a modest two-story home close to the UW–Madison campus.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] His children followed in his footsteps as teachers and naturalists: Aldo Starker Leopold (1913–1983) was a wildlife biologist and professor at UC Berkeley; Luna B.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Leopold purchased 80 acres in the sand country of central Wisconsin.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] The once-forested region had been logged, swept by repeated fires, overgrazed by dairy cows, and left barren.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] He put his theories to work in the field and eventually set to work writing his best-selling *A Sand County Almanac* (1949) which was finished just prior to his death.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Aldo Leopold died from a heart attack on April 21, 1948, while helping his neighbors control a grass fire by his farm in Baraboo, Wisconsin.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Leopold's home is an official landmark of the city of Madison.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Early on, Leopold was assigned to hunt and kill bears, wolves, and mountain lions in New Mexico.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Local ranchers hated these predators because of livestock losses, but Leopold came to respect the animals.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] One day after fatally shooting a wolf, Leopold reached the animal and was transfixed by a "fierce green fire dying in her eyes." That experience changed him and put him on the path toward an ecocentric outlook.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] He developed an ecological ethic that replaced the earlier wilderness ethic that stressed the need for human dominance.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] His rethinking the importance of predators in the balance of nature has resulted in the return of bears and mountain lions to New Mexico wilderness areas.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] By the early 1920s, Leopold had concluded that a particular kind of preservation should be embraced in the national forests of the American West.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] He was prompted to this by the rampant building of roads to accommodate the "proliferation of the automobile" and the related increasingly heavy recreational demands placed on public lands.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] He was the first to employ the term "wilderness" to describe such preservation.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Over the next two decades, he added ethical and scientific rationales to his defense of the wilderness concept.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Leopold believed that it is easier to maintain wilderness than to create it.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Leopold thus rejected the utilitarianism of conservationists such as Theodore Roosevelt.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] By the 1930s, Leopold had become one of the first Americans to publish extensively on the startup discipline of wildlife management.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] He advocated the scientific management of wildlife habitats by both public and private landholders rather than a reliance on game refuges, hunting laws, and other methods intended to protect specific species of desired game.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] The concept of "wilderness" also took on a new meaning; Leopold no longer saw it as a hunting or recreational ground, but as an arena for a healthy biotic community, including wolves and mountain lions.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] In 1935, he helped found the Wilderness Society, dedicated to expanding and protecting the nation's wilderness areas.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] He regarded the society as "one of the focal points of a new attitude—an intelligent humility toward Man's place in nature." Science writer Connie Barlow says Leopold wrote eloquently from a perspective that today would be called Religious Naturalism.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Though often forgotten, thinking about population dynamics and consumption also shaped Leopold's ecological vision in profound ways.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] By studying wildlife population fluctuations, Leopold extended many of the ideas about carrying capacity and environmental degradation that Raymond Pearl and Edward Murray East had articulated, and these ideas, in turn, shaped his path-breaking ideas of ecological interconnection.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Moreover, although later readers associate Leopold with wildlife ecology, his career helps show how Malthusian ideas of human society intertwined and overlapped with ideas of nature.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] He was greatly influenced by ecologists who themselves gleaned ideas from Malthusian models of human society, and himself often thought of human events—especially the Great Depression and World War II—in terms of the models of population and consumption that he was developing for animals.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] One of the most influential books for Leopold during that period was *Our Vanishing Wildlife* by William Temple Hornaday.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] As one of the earliest works dedicated entirely to the threats facing wild game populations this book significantly shaped Leopold's views.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] The book sharpened his focus on the importance of game protection, a concern that would remain central to his thinking for many years to come.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Leopold's nature writing is notable for its simple directness.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] His portrayals of various natural environments through which he had moved, or had known for many years, displayed impressive intimacy with what exists and happens in nature.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] This includes detailed diaries and journals of his Forest Service activity, hunting and field experience, as well as observations and activities at his Sand County farm.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] He offered frank criticism of the harm he believed was frequently done to natural systems (such as land) out of a sense of a culture or society's sovereign ownership over the land base – eclipsing any sense of a community of life to which humans belong.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] The book was published in 1949, shortly after Leopold's death.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] It was structured in a series of monthly essays where he went in depth about land ethics and nature.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Several of these monthly essays were accompanied with sketches from the different landscapes and plants he found.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Additionally, he would have philosophical segments that would contribute to his land ethic concepts.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Thinking Like a Mountain was originally written during World War II and shows that Leopold's thinking was shaped by that global cataclysm.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] In "The Land Ethic", a chapter in *A Sand County Almanac*, Leopold delves into conservation in "The Ecological Conscience" section.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] He wrote: "Conservation is a state of harmony between men and land." He noted that conservation guidelines at the time boiled down to: "obey the law, vote right, join some organizations, and practice what conservation is profitable on your own land; the government will do the rest." (p.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Aldo Leopold's contributions to conservation, particularly his role in establishing the Gila Wilderness Area, are deeply intertwined with the evolution of his philosophical views.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] In the early 20th century, Leopold's work with the U.S.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Forest Service in the American Southwest was grounded in the agency's utilitarian ethos, which prioritized resource extraction and economic productivity.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] As a forester in Arizona and New Mexico, Leopold initially approached wildlife management with a focus on maximizing game species for human benefit, a perspective aligned with the Progressive Era's emphasis on efficient resource use.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Leopold's philosophy began to evolve in the 1910s and 1920s, driven by field observations, ecological consequences of his early practices, and intellectual growth.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] A pivotal moment in Leopold's transformation occurred around 1909–1910, during his early years in the Apache National Forest.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] In his essay “Thinking Like a Mountain”, Leopold recounts shooting a wolf and watching it die, observing “a fierce green fire” in its eyes.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] This visceral experience, coupled with witnessing the subsequent ecological fallout, profoundly altered his perspective.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] The incident highlighted the role of predators in maintaining ecological balance.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Without wolves, deer populations surged, overgrazing vegetation and triggering a cascade of environmental damage, including soil erosion and loss of biodiversity.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Leopold realized that “the mountain” required all its components—predators, prey, and plants—to function healthily.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] This moment marked a shift from viewing wildlife in isolation to understanding ecosystems as dynamic, interdependent systems.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] It planted the seed for his later ecocentric philosophy, where no single species, including humans, could be prioritized at the expense of the whole.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] In "Marshland Elegy", an excerpt from *A Sand County Almanac,* Leopold describes the process of destruction for American marshland as well as the efforts to reinvigorate those marshlands after that destruction.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Leopold speak both to the way in which the halting of farmland development in these areas represents positive change for the cranes and other wildlife that relies on marshes as well as the limitations of the strategies implemented by conservationists in the issue.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Leopold criticized conservation strategy in that to make the public cherish the communities we conserve they need to "see and fondle" them which can make the conservation effort self-defeating.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] At the time this essay was written Sandhill Cranes had dwindled to merely 25 breeding pairs in Wisconsin, luckily since then the crane population has recovered with the midwest now being home to over 15,000 sandhill cranes.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] These efforts were inspired by this essay and carried out by the Aldo Leopold foundation.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] These efforts give a positive example to be looked to for future conservation efforts.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Game Management is deemed Leopold's most important work as it founded a new science by combining the likes of agriculture, biology, ecology, and other sciences.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] This book brought about a revolution within conservation and placed Leopold as the founder of the Department of Game Management at The University of Wisconsin.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] For more than 40 years after its publication, it was the leading textbook in the field of wildlife management.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Published nearly 45 years after the death of Leopold, The River of the Mother of God, includes 59 essays drawn from Leopold's unpublished manuscripts found at The University of Wisconsin and Leopold's overlooked published work.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] This collection is titled after one of Leopold's most popular essays from 1924, “The River of the Mother of God,” but it spans Leopold's life discussing themes of wilderness preservation, ecology, agriculture, land ethics, and natural esthetics from his teenage years until his last years.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] This work dives into a deeper view of Leopold and shows the lasting impact he made on the field of conservation.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] In *A Sand County Almanac*, Aldo Leopold's essay “A Man’s Leisure Time” provides us with a thoughtful examination of how leisure enriches our lives by deepening our connection with nature.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Leopold believed that how one spends their free time is a good indicator of one's intelligence and character.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Leopold states, “How miserable are the idle hours of the ignorant man!” contributing to his idea that leisure time is meaningful and it is important to take in the nature around when present with the opportunity.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] According to Leopold, leisure activities should not be relaxing time but ways to achieve personal growth and understanding.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] He describes hobbies as "a defiance of the contemporary," suggesting that they allow individuals to step away from the relentless pace of modern life and engage in activities that are rewarding and enriching.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Leopold highlights that such pursuits, whether it's collecting fossils or cultivating a garden, can lead to a profound appreciation of the land and how important and amazing nature is.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] In this chapter, Mr.Leopold encourages the reader to consider what they do with their free or leisure time in their life.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Leopold advocates for activities that promote a deeper understanding of the natural world.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] In 1933, Aldo Leopold became Professor of Game Management at the University of Wisconsin-Madison, the first position of its kind in the country.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Through his contributions to and knowledge of the field, he developed curricula and ran the program, which was eventually redubbed Wildlife Ecology.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] "Game Management" during this time meant the scientific study and the practical application of techniques for maintaining a healthy wildlife population, especially those that are hunted for sport.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Through his expertise, the area of wildlife management grew from just managing populations within life to a larger egocialcal approach to managing wildlife population.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Game management was a branch of conservation biology to Aldo Leopold.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] He was concerned about the whole ecological balance of the environment and not just one species.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] He created a field that was hit every area ecology, policy, forestry, and ethics.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] He even published a textbook for his class titles "Game management", also published in 1933.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] In 1950 The Wildlife Society honored Leopold by creating an annual award in his name.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Furthermore, the foundation formed a Leopold Conservation Award to recognize farmers, forestland owners, and private land owners for inspirational conservation efforts and leadership within land ethics.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] The *Aldo Leopold Foundation* of Baraboo, Wisconsin, was founded in 1982 by Aldo and Estella Leopold's five children as a 501(c)3 not-for-profit conservation organization whose mission is "to foster the land ethic through the legacy of Aldo Leopold".
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] The Aldo Leopold Foundation owns and manages the original Aldo Leopold Shack and Farm and 300 surrounding acres, in addition to several other parcels.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Its headquarters is the green-built *Leopold Center* where it conducts educational and land stewardship programs.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] The foundation also acts as the executor of Leopold's literary estate, encourages scholarship on Leopold, and serves as a clearinghouse for information regarding Leopold, his work, and his ideas.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] It provides interpretive resources and tours for thousands of visitors annually, distributes a curriculum about how to use Leopold's writing and ideas in environmental education.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] The center maintains a robust website and numerous print resources.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] In 2012, in collaboration with the United States Forest Service, the foundation and the Center for Humans and Nature released the first full-length film about Leopold, titled *Green Fire: Aldo Leopold and a Land Ethic for Our Time*.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] The film aired on public television stations across the nation and won a Midwest regional Emmy award in the documentary category.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] The Aldo Leopold Wilderness in New Mexico's Gila National Forest was named after him in 1980.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] The Leopold Center for Sustainable Agriculture was established in 1987 at Iowa State University in Ames.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Since its founding, it has pioneered new forms of sustainable agriculture practices.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Forest Service established the Aldo Leopold Wilderness Research Institute at the University of Montana, Missoula in 1993.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] The Aldo Leopold Neighborhood Historic District, which includes Leopold's former home in Albuquerque, New Mexico, was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2002.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] The Aldo Leopold Legacy Trail System, a system of 42 state trails in Wisconsin, was created by the state in 2007 to honor Leopold's contributions to the conservation and outdoor recreation.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] This trail covers more than 1,700 miles across the state of Wisconsin.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Many of the trails pass through forests, scenics natural areas, and state parks.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] There are signs, along the trails, to showcase information about Leopold's life, his conservation work, and natural information about the surrounding area.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] The Leopold Center for Sustainable Agriculture in Iowa, created through the 1987 Iowa Groundwater Protection Act is committed to "new ways to farm profitably while conserving natural resources as well as reducing negative environmental and social impacts".
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] An organization, the Leopold Heritage Group, is "dedicated to promoting the global legacy of Aldo Leopold in his hometown of Burlington, Iowa." This groups preserves and shares Leopold's legacy by providing local events, educational programs, and conservation projects.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] The "Leopold Heritage Group", supports efforts to maintain Leopold-relates sites around the area for example, his childhood home and many places that he has explored as a child.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] In 1985, Leopold was inducted along with John Muir, a naturalist and preservationist, as the first inductees to the Wisconsin Conservation Hall of Fame.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] The Hall of Fame is located in Stevens Point, Wisconsin, it was created to recognize the individuals who have made important contributions to conserving the natural state of resources around the state.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] The Leopold Residence Hall at the University of Wisconsin-Madison was named after him.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Leopold's Preserve in Haymarket, Virginia was established in 2014.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] This preserve is a 380-acre park that is committed to preserving diverse ecosystems, natural scenes, and protecting threatened land from industrial and commercial development.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] Aldo Leopold is well known for being the founder of wildlife management, he played a key role in establishing ethics in the wildlife world.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/aldo-leopold] He was a driving force behind the creation of the Gila National Forest Wilderness, and his legacy lives on today as the Gila National Forest has been standing strong since 1924, when the National Forest was created.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] In classical political economy and especially Karl Marx's critique of political economy, a **commodity** is any good or service ("products" or "activities") produced by human labour and offered as a product for general sale on the market.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] Some other priced goods are also treated as commodities, e.g. human labor-power, works of art and natural resources, even though they may not be produced specifically for the market, or be non-reproducible goods.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] This problem was extensively debated by Adam Smith, David Ricardo, and Karl Rodbertus-Jagetzow, among others.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] Value and price are not equivalent terms in Marxist economics, and theorising the specific relationship of value to market price has been a challenge for Marxist economists.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] In Marx's theory, a commodity is something that is bought and sold, or exchanged in a relationship of trade.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] Price is then the *monetary expression* of exchange-value, but exchange value could also be expressed as a direct trading ratio between two commodities without using money, and goods could be priced using different valuations or criteria.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] According to the labor theory of value, product-values in an open market are regulated by the average socially necessary labour time required to produce them, and price relativities of products are ultimately governed by the law of value.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] Commodity-trade, Marx argues, historically begins at the boundaries of separate economic communities based otherwise on a *non-commercial* form of production.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] Thus, producers trade in those goods of which those producers, have episodic or permanent surpluses to their own requirements, and they aim to obtain different goods with an equal value in return.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] Marx refers to this as "simple exchange" which implies what Frederick Engels calls "simple commodity production".
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] At first, goods may not even be intentionally produced for the explicit purpose of exchanging them, but as a regular market for goods develops and a cash economy grows, this becomes more and more the case, and production increasingly becomes integrated in commodity trade.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] Even so, in simple commodity production, not all inputs and outputs of the production process are necessarily commodities or priced goods, and it is compatible with a variety of different relations of production ranging from self-employment and family labour to serfdom and slavery.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] Typically, however, it is the producer himself who trades his surpluses.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] However, as the division of labour becomes more complex, a class of merchants emerges which specialises in trading commodities, buying here and selling there, without producing products themselves, and parallel to this, property owners emerge who extend credit and charge rents.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] This process goes together with the increased use of money, and the aim of merchants, bankers and renters becomes to gain *income* from the trade, by acting as intermediaries between producers and consumers.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] The transformation of a labor-product into a commodity (its "marketing") is in reality not a simple process, but has many technical and social preconditions.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] The existence of a social need for it (a market demand) that must be met through trade, or at any event cannot be met otherwise.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] The legally sanctioned assertion of private ownership rights to the commodity.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] The enforcement of these rights, so that ownership is secure.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] The transferability of these private rights from one owner to another.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] The (physical) transferability or transmission of the commodity itself, i.e. the ability to store, package, preserve, send and transport it from one owner to another.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] The imposition of exclusivity of access to the commodity.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] The possibility of the owner to use or consume the commodity privately.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] Guarantees about the quality and safety of the commodity, and possibly a guarantee of replacement or service, should it fail to function as intended (see also Complaint tablet to Ea-nāṣir).
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] Thus, the "commodification" of a good or service often involves a considerable practical accomplishment in trade.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] It is a process that may be influenced not just by economic or technical factors, but also political and cultural factors, insofar as it involves property rights, claims to access to resources, and guarantees about quality or safety of use.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] In absolute terms, exchange values can also be measured as quantities of average labour-hours.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] Commodities which contain the same amount of socially necessary labor have the same exchange value.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] By contrast, prices are normally measured in money-units.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] For practical purposes, prices are, however, usually preferable to labour-hours, as units of account, although in capitalist work processes the two are related to each other (see labor power).
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] The hyphens ("-") here refer to a transaction applying to an exchange involving goods or money; the dots in the last-mentioned circuit ("...") indicate that a value-forming process ("P") occurs *in between* purchase of commodities and the sales of different commodities.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] Thus, while at first merchants are intermediaries between producers and consumers, later capitalist *production* becomes an intermediary between buyers and sellers of commodities.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] In that case, the valuation of labour is determined by the value of its products.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] It is possible to extend the Marxian circuit schema's to portray the more complex sequences of phases in international trade and finance.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] This type of representation was pioneered by the French Marxian economist Christian Palloix in his study of multinational firms in the early 1970s.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] The reifying effects of universalised trade in commodities, involving a process Marx calls "commodity fetishism", mean that social relations become expressed as relations between things; for example, price relations.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] Markets mediate a complex network of interdependencies and supply chains emerging among people who may not even know who produced the goods they buy, or where they were produced.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] How quantities of use-values are allocated in a market economy depends mainly on their exchange value, and this allocation is mediated by the "cash nexus".
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] In Marx's analysis of the capitalist mode of production, commodity sales increase the amount of exchange-value in the possession of the owners of capital, i.e., they yield profit and thus augment their capital (capital accumulation).
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] These components reflect respectively labour costs, the cost of materials and operating expenses including depreciation, and generic profit.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] In capitalism, Marx argues, commodity values are commercially expressed as the prices of production of commodities (cost-price + average profit).
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] Prices of production are established jointly by average input costs *and* by the ruling profit margins applying to outputs sold.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] They reflect the fact that production has become totally integrated into the circuits of commodity trade, in which capital accumulation becomes the dominant motive.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] But what prices of production simultaneously hide is the social nature of the valorisation process, i.e. how an increase in capital-value occurs through production.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] Likewise, in considering the gross output of capitalist production in an economy as a whole, Marx divides its value into these four components.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] He argues that the total new value added in production, which he calls the value product, consists of the equivalent of variable capital, plus surplus value.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] Thus, the workers produce by their labor both a new value equal to their own wages, plus an additional new value which is claimed by capitalists by virtue of their ownership and supply of productive capital.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] By producing new capital in the form of new commodities, Marx argues the working class continuously reproduces the capitalist relations of production; by their work, workers create a new value distributed as both labour-income and property-income.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] If, as free workers, they choose to stop working, the system begins to break down; hence, capitalist civilisation strongly emphasizes the work ethic, regardless of religious belief.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] People must work, because work is the source of new value, profits and capital.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] Marx acknowledged explicitly that not all commodities are products of human labour; all kinds of things can be traded "as if" they are commodities, so long as property rights can be attached to them.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] These are "fictitious commodities" or "pseudo-commodities" or "fiduciary commodities", i.e. their existence as commodities is only nominal or conventional.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] They may not even be tangible objects, but exist only ideally.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/article-of-commerce] A property right or financial claim, for instance, may be traded as a commodity.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] Baraboo is home to the Circus World Museum and the former headquarters and winter home of the Ringling Brothers Circus.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] Ringling Theatre is an active landmark in the city.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] Baraboo is near Devil's Lake State Park and Aldo Leopold Shack and Farm.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] The Ho-Chunk Nation of Wisconsin has an active cultural and community presence in the Baraboo area.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] The area around Baraboo was the site of a Kickapoo village as early as 1665.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] The current community was established by Abe Wood in 1838, and was originally known as the village of Adams.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] In 1839 several settlers arrived and started building cabins, and a saw mill.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] In 1846 it became the county seat of Sauk County after a fierce fight with the nearby village of Reedsburg.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] In 1852, the village was renamed "Baraboo", after the nearby river.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] It was incorporated as a village in 1866 and as a city in 1882.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] In the 1860s, the city had surpassed a population of 2,000, and many businesses started to form, including grocery stores, banks, and hotels.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] In 1872, the Chicago and North Western Railway (C&NW) was built.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] Baraboo became home to several saw mills during this time, because of its location near the Baraboo and Wisconsin Rivers.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] In 1884, the Ringling Brothers Circus was established in Baraboo by circus performers and tourers the Ringling brothers, after they settled in the city in 1875 and performed their first show in Mazomanie, Wisconsin in 1882.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] Several other circuses then came to the city, which earned Baraboo the nickname "Circus City".
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] Located south of Baraboo in the Census-designated place of Bluffview, was the Badger Ordnance Works, which was the largest munitions factory in the world during World War II.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] It was later demolished and now the land is a part of the Sauk Prairie Recreation Area.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] Cirrus, a manufacturer of single-engine aircraft, was founded in a rural Baraboo barn in 1984 by the Klapmeier brothers.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] After a few years of designing the VK-30, they relocated to the Baraboo–Dells Airport and in 1994 moved the company to its present-day home in Duluth, Minnesota.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] According to the United States Census Bureau, the city has a total area of 7.47 square miles (19.35 km2), of which 7.39 square miles (19.14 km2) is land and 0.08 square miles (0.21 km2) is water.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] West Baraboo, a suburb of Baraboo, borders the city on its west side.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] Baraboo gives its name to the Baraboo Syncline, a doubly plunging, asymmetric syncline in Proterozoic-aged Baraboo quartzite.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] Researchers at the University of Wisconsin, particularly Charles R.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] Van Hise, used the syncline to demonstrate that small-scale deformational structures in isolated outcrops reflect larger regional structures and that sedimentary structures could indicate the original top-facing direction within elaborately deformed strata.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] These two principles sparked a global revolution in structural geology during the 1920s.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] The nearby Baraboo Hills are designated one of the "Last Great Places" by the Nature Conservancy because of its rare rocks, plants and animals.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] The hills were created by glacial action, and in some points poke up from the flat terrain to form a stark contrast.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] Some of these features were created when a glacial pocket was formed during the Wisconsin glaciation where the advance of the glacier halted, along the edge of what is known as the Driftless Area.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] Devil's Lake State Park, Wisconsin's largest state park, contains large areas of the Baraboo Hills.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] According to the Köppen Climate Classification system, Baraboo has a warm-summer humid continental climate, abbreviated "Dfb" on climate maps.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] The hottest temperature recorded in Baraboo was 103 °F (39.4 °C) on July 5–7, 2012, while the coldest temperature recorded was −45 °F (−42.8 °C) on January 30, 1951.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] Baraboo forms the core of the United States Census Bureau's Baraboo Micropolitan Statistical Area, which includes all of Sauk County (2000 population: 55,225).
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] The Baraboo μSA is just northwest of the Madison metropolitan area, with which it forms the Census Bureau's Baraboo-Madison Consolidated Metropolitan Statistical Area.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] As of the 2020 census, Baraboo had a population of 12,556.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] 22.0% of residents were under the age of 18 and 19.6% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] For every 100 females there were 95.2 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 93.3 males age 18 and over.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] 97.8% of residents lived in urban areas, while 2.2% lived in rural areas.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] There were 5,442 households in Baraboo, of which 27.3% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] Of all households, 40.7% were married-couple households, 20.7% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 29.9% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] About 35.0% of all households were made up of individuals and 15.8% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] The population density was 1,709.2 inhabitants per square mile (659.9/km2).
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] There were 5,776 housing units at an average density of 786.3 per square mile (303.6/km2), of which 5.8% were vacant.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] The homeowner vacancy rate was 1.0% and the rental vacancy rate was 6.5%.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] As of the census of 2010, there were 12,048 people, 5,161 households, and 3,016 families residing in the city.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] The population density was 1,630.3 inhabitants per square mile (629.5/km2).
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] There were 5,619 housing units at an average density of 760.4 per square mile (293.6/km2).
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] The racial makeup of the city was 94.0% White, 1.3% African American, 1.0% Native American, 0.5% Asian, 0.1% Pacific Islander, 1.5% from other races, and 1.6% from two or more races.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] Hispanic or Latino people of any race were 3.7% of the population.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] There were 5,161 households, of which 30.2% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 41.1% were married couples living together, 11.8% had a female householder with no husband present, 5.5% had a male householder with no wife present, and 41.6% were non-families.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] 34.4% of all households were made up of individuals, and 14.7% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] The average household size was 2.26 and the average family size was 2.89.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] The median age in the city was 38 years.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] 23.8% of residents were under the age of 18; 8% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 27.5% were from 25 to 44; 25.1% were from 45 to 64; and 15.6% were 65 years of age or older.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] The gender makeup of the city was 49.1% male and 50.9% female.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] As of the census of 2000, there were 10,711 people, 4,467 households, and 2,733 families residing in the city.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] The population density was 2,030.2 people per square mile (783.2/km2).
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] There were 4,718 housing units at an average density of 894.3 per square mile (345.0 persons/km2).
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] The racial makeup of the city was 97.12% White, 0.51% African American, 0.77% Native American, 0.52% Asian, 0.00% Pacific Islander, 0.41% from other races, and 0.66% from two or more races.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] 1.57% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] There were 4,467 households, out of which 31.0% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 46.9% were married couples living together, 10.8% had a female householder with no husband present, and 38.8% were non-families.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] 32.1% of all households were made up of individuals, and 13.5% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] The average household size was 2.33 and the average family size was 2.96.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] In the city, the population was spread out, with 24.9% under the age of 18, 8.8% from 18 to 24, 30.5% from 25 to 44, 20.1% from 45 to 64, and 15.7% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] For every 100 females, there were 93.0 males.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 90.0 males.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] The median income for a household in the city was $38,375, and the median income for a family was $48,149.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] Males had a median income of $32,775 versus $22,813 for females.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] The per capita income for the city was $19,304.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] 6.6% of the population and 4.7% of families were below the poverty line, including 6.7% of those under the age of 18 and 10.0% of those age 65 or older.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] Baraboo includes the Downtown Baraboo Historic District, which consists of 75 commercial and civic buildings built between 1870 and 1938.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] The Sauk County Courthouse is in the center of the district, and it serves the county.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] Other historic buildings in the city include Carnegie-Schadde Memorial Public Library, William Clark House, Gust Brothers' Store, Island Woolen Company Office Building, Walworth D.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] Ringling House, Charles Ringling House, Charles and Anna Ruhland House, Seven Gables, Thompson House Hotel, A.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] Tuttle Estate and Jacob Van Orden House.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] The Aldo Leopold Shack and Farm near Baraboo was acquired in the 1930s as a family summer retreat by the noted conservationist and writer Aldo Leopold and is the landscape that inspired his conservation ethic and the writing of his best-known work, *A Sand County Almanac*.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] Hank Snow's 1959 song "I've Been Everywhere", covered by Johnny Cash, mentions visiting Baraboo.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] A city hall building opened in 1967, and another location finished construction in 2018 at a cost of $9 million.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] A campus of the University of Wisconsin–Platteville Baraboo Sauk County is located in Baraboo.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] The Baraboo School District has four elementary schools serving students in grades 1 through 5, one kindergarten center, one middle school and one high school (Baraboo High School).
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] There are also three parochial schools: St.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] Joseph's Catholic School, which serves Pre-K through sixth grade; St.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] John's Lutheran School of the WELS, serving Pre-K through eighth grade; and Community Christian School, serving 4K through high school.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] The Baraboo Public Library serves the community.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] The former Free Congregational Society church was demolished by 1902 for the library's construction.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] The Baraboo-Wisconsin Dells Airport (KDLL) serves the city and surrounding communities, and is located on Bus.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] There is access to Interstate 90/94 nearby.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] The Wisconsin & Southern Railroad provides freight rail service to Baraboo via the Reedsburg Subdivision, the nearest Amtrak passenger rail station is in neighboring Wisconsin Dells.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] Dial-a-ride transit service is available in the city through Baraboo Transit.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] Baraboo station was located on the Chicago and North Western Railway and served both passengers and freight traffic as well as housing the Madison Division offices of the C&NW.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] Passenger service to the depot ended in 1963 with the elimination of the *Rochester 400*.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] As of 2022, the Sauk County Historical Society hopes to restore the depot into a museum and community gathering space.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/baraboo-wisconsin] Megabus offers daily bus service from Baraboo to La Crosse and Milwaukee Intermodal Station via Madison.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/biotic-community] A **biocenosis** (UK English, **biocoenosis**, also **biocenose**, **biocoenose**, **biotic community**, **biological community**, **ecological community**, **life assemblage**), coined by Karl Möbius in 1877, describes the interacting organisms living together in a habitat (biotope).
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/biotic-community] The use of this term has declined in the 21st сentury.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/biotic-community] In the palaeontological literature, the term distinguishes "life assemblages", which reflect the original living community, living together at one place and time.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/biotic-community] In other words, it is an assemblage of fossils or a community of specific time, which is different from "death assemblages" (thanatocoenoses).
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/biotic-community] No palaeontological assemblage will ever completely represent the original biological community (i.e. the biocoenosis, in the sense used by an ecologist); the term thus has somewhat different meanings in a palaeontological and an ecological context.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/biotic-community] The geographical extent of a biocenose is limited by the requirement of a more or less uniform species composition.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/biotic-community] An ecosystem, originally defined by Tansley (1935), is a biotic community (or biocenosis) along with its physical environment (or *biotope*).
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/biotic-community] In ecological studies, biocenosis is the emphasis on relationships between species in an area.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/biotic-community] These relationships are an additional consideration to the interaction of each species with the physical environment.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/biotic-community] Biotic communities vary in size, and larger ones may contain smaller ones.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/biotic-community] Species interactions are evident in food or feeding relationships.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/biotic-community] A method of delineating biotic communities is to map the food network to identify which species feed upon which others and then determine the system boundary as the one that can be drawn through the fewest consumption links relative to the number of species within the boundary.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/biotic-community] Mapping biotic communities is important identifying sites needing environmental protection, such as the British Site of Special Scientific Interest (SSSIs).
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/biotic-community] The Australian Department of the Environment and Heritage maintains a register of *Threatened Species and Threatened Ecological Communities* under the Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999 (EPBC Act).
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/charles-w-schwartz] He received his AB in Zoology from the University of Missouri in 1938.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/charles-w-schwartz] A graduate assistantship during his MA led Schwartz to work with Elizabeth Reeder, a Ph.D. candidate.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/charles-w-schwartz] They married in 1938 and later had three children.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/charles-w-schwartz] In 1940, Schwartz completed his MA and began work at the Missouri Conservation Commission as a biologist.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/charles-w-schwartz] Schwartz's career with the Missouri Department of Conservation lasted for thirty-nine years.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/charles-w-schwartz] A short stint from 1946 to 1947 was spent in Hawaii studying wildlife conditions for Hawaii's Board of Agriculture and Forestry.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/charles-w-schwartz] Throughout the late twentieth century, the Schwartzes wrote and illustrated books, created films, and made artwork on wildlife and conservation topics.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/charles-w-schwartz] In 1949, *Game Birds of Hawaii* was published and selected by the Wildlife Society as the best publication in wildlife management and ecology for 1949–1950.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/charles-w-schwartz] Several other films won awards, including a 1952 CONI Grand Medal for *Bobwhite through the Year* and the American Association for Conservation Information best North American wildlife movie award in 1959 for *Story of the Mourning Dove*.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/charles-w-schwartz] In 1949, Schwartz illustrated Aldo Leopold's landmark book on conservation, *A Sand County Almanac: And Sketches Here and There*.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/charles-w-schwartz] Another Schwartz collaboration, *The Wild Mammals of Missouri*, was co-published by the University of Missouri Press and the Missouri Department of Conservation.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/charles-w-schwartz] Containing over four hundred illustrations and information about sixty-six species, *Wild Mammals* proved to be one of their most important works.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/charles-w-schwartz] The American Association for Conservation Information selected it as the outstanding wildlife book in 1959 and revised editions were published in 1981 and 2001.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/charles-w-schwartz] Schwartz's artwork was used for Missouri trout and duck stamps, conservation fundraising for the Conservation Federation of Missouri and other efforts, and books by other Missouri wildlife writers.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/charles-w-schwartz] From 1965 to 1987, he completed murals for the Missouri Department of Conservation headquarters in Jefferson City.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/charles-w-schwartz] He remained active as an artist and outdoorsman.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/charles-w-schwartz] He died from pancreatic cancer at his home in Coeur d'Alene.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/charles-w-schwartz] A posthumous book, *About Mammals and How They Live*, was completed by Libby, published in 1993, and selected by the Wildlife Society for its 1994 Conservation Education Award.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] Conservation goals include conserving habitat, preventing deforestation, maintaining soil organic matter, halting species extinction, reducing overfishing, and mitigating climate change.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] Different philosophical outlooks guide conservationists towards these different goals.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] Philosophers have attached intrinsic value to different aspects of nature, whether this is individual organisms (biocentrism) or ecological wholes such as species or ecosystems (ecoholism).
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] More utilitarian schools of conservation have an anthropocentric outlook and seek a proper valuation of local and global impacts of human activity upon nature in their effect upon human wellbeing, now and to posterity.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] How such values are assessed and exchanged among people determines the social, political and personal restraints and imperatives by which conservation is practiced.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] This is a view common in the modern environmental movement.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] There is increasing interest in extending the responsibility for human wellbeing to include the welfare of sentient animals.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] In 2022 the United Kingdom introduced the Animal Welfare (Sentience) Act which lists all vertebrates, decapod crustaceans and cephalopods as sentient beings.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] Branches of conservation ethics focusing on sentient individuals include ecofeminism and compassionate conservation.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] In the United States of America, the year 1864 saw the publication of two books which laid the foundation for Romantic and Utilitarian conservation traditions in America.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] The posthumous publication of Henry David Thoreau's *Walden* established the grandeur of unspoiled nature as a citadel to nourish the spirit of man.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] A very different book from George Perkins Marsh, *Man and Nature*, later subtitled "The Earth as Modified by Human Action", catalogued his observations of man exhausting and altering the land from which his sustenance derives.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] National Parks are important in the history of nature conservation, and some of the first parks were established in the USA.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] The historian Al Runte described how they first were set up and emphasized the role of "worthless lands", i.e. that mainly land of low commercial interest is protected, such as alpine and dry habitats.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] In addition, tourism, aesthetics, and "monumentalism" are important, according to Al Runte.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] The consumer conservation ethic has been defined as the attitudes and behaviors held and engaged in by individuals and families that ultimately serve to reduce overall societal consumption of energy.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] The conservation movement has emerged from the advancements of moral reasoning.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] Increasing numbers of philosophers and scientists have made its maturation possible by considering the relationships between human beings and organisms with the same rigor.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] These practices are used to slow down the accelerating rate in which extinction is occurring at.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] The origins of this ethic can be traced back to many different philosophical and religious beliefs; that is, these practices has been advocated for centuries.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] In the past, conservationism has been categorized under a spectrum of views, including anthropocentric, utilitarian conservationism, and radical eco-centric green eco-political views.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] More recently, the three major movements has been grouped to become what we now know as conservation ethic.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] The person credited with formulating the conservation ethic in the United States is former president, Theodore Roosevelt.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] The term "conservation" was coined by Gifford Pinchot in 1907.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] He told his close friend United States President Theodore Roosevelt who used it for a national conference of governors in 1908.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] In common usage, the term refers to the activity of systematically protecting natural resources such as forests, including biological diversity.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] While this usage is not new, the idea of biological conservation has been applied to the principles of ecology, biogeography, anthropology, economy, and sociology to maintain biodiversity.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] The term "conservation" itself may cover the concepts such as cultural diversity, genetic diversity, and the concept of movements environmental conservation, seedbank curation (preservation of seeds), and gene bank coordination (preservation of animals' genetic material).
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] These are often summarized as the priority to respect diversity.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] Much recent movement in conservation can be considered a resistance to commercialism and globalization.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] Slow Food is a consequence of rejecting these as moral priorities, and embracing a slower and more locally focused lifestyle.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] Sustainable living is a lifestyle that people are beginning to adopt, promoting to make decisions that would help protect biodiversity.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] The small lifestyle changes that promote sustainability will eventually accumulate into the proliferation of biological diversity.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] Regulating the ecolabeling of products from fisheries, controlling for sustainable food production, or keeping the lights off during the day are some examples of sustainable living.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] However, sustainable living is not a simple and uncomplicated approach.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] We do not pretend that the process is easy or straightforward." Simply put, sustainable living does make a difference by compiling many individual actions that encourage the protection of biological diversity.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] Distinct trends exist regarding conservation development.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] The need for conserving land has only recently intensified during what some scholars refer to as the Capitalocene epoch.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] This era marks the beginning of colonialism, globalization, and the Industrial Revolution that has led to global land change as well as climate change.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] Nowadays, officially more than 10 percent of the world is legally protected in some way or the other, and in practice, private fundraising is insufficient to pay for the effective management of so much land with protective status.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] Protected areas in developing countries, where probably as many as 70–80 percent of the species of the world live, still enjoy very little effective management and protection.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] Some countries, such as Mexico, have non-profit civil organizations and landowners dedicated to protecting vast private property, such is the case of Hacienda Chichen's Maya Jungle Reserve and Bird Refuge in Chichen Itza, Yucatán.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] The Adopt A Ranger Foundation has calculated that worldwide about 140,000 rangers are needed for the protected areas in developing and transition countries.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] There are no data on how many rangers are employed at the moment, but probably less than half the protected areas in developing and transition countries have any rangers at all and those that have them are at least 50% short.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] This means that there would be a worldwide ranger deficit of 105,000 rangers in the developing and transition countries.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] The terms *conservation* and *preservation* are frequently conflated outside the academic, scientific, and professional kinds of literature.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] During the environmental movement of the early 20th century, two opposing factions emerged: conservationists and preservationists.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] Anne Claus presents a distinction for conservation practices.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] Claus divides conservation into conservation-far and conservation-near.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] Conservation-far is the means of protecting nature by separating it and safeguarding it from humans.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] Means of doing this include the creation of preserves or national parks.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] They are meant to keep the flora and fauna away from human influence and have become a staple method in the west.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] Conservation-near however is conservation via connection.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] The method of reconnecting people to nature through traditions and beliefs to foster a desire to protect nature.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] The basis is that instead of forcing compliance to separate from nature onto the people, instead conservationists work with locals and their traditions to find conservation efforts that work for all.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] Evidence-based conservation is the application of evidence in conservation management actions and policy making.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] It is defined as systematically assessing scientific information from published, peer-reviewed publications and texts, practitioners' experiences, independent expert assessment, and local and indigenous knowledge on a specific conservation topic.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] This includes assessing the current effectiveness of different management interventions, threats and emerging problems, and economic factors.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] Evidence-based conservation was organized based on the observations that decision making in conservation was based on intuition and/or practitioner experience often disregarding other forms of evidence of successes and failures (e.g. scientific information).
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] This has led to costly and poor outcomes.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] Evidence-based conservation provides access to information that will support decision making through an evidence-based framework of "what works" in conservation.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] The evidence-based approach to conservation is based on evidence-based practice which started in medicine and later spread to nursing, education, psychology, and other fields.
[src:a-sand-county-almanac/conservation-ethic] It is part of the larger movement towards evidence-based practices.
